# WASM training interface (JouleQuest)

Scope: work on the **in-process WASM path** for RL training (compact engine, WASI exports, Python wasmtime client). Not generic project advice.

Full motivation and interface shape: [WASM_TRAINING_INTERFACE.md](../../WASM_TRAINING_INTERFACE.md) at repo root.

## Go (TinyGo WASM / compact engine)

- Training/WASM game logic lives under **`src/compact/`** (`compact/params`, `compact/game`; later `compact/client` for exports). Prefer extending that tree over growing WASM-only code inside `engine/`.
- **TinyGo (recent release, ≥ 0.34)** is the planned compiler for the training WASM binary ([releases](https://github.com/tinygo-org/tinygo/releases)). Use **reactor-style** builds with **`-target=wasm-unknown`** (see upstream [hello-wasm-unknown](https://github.com/tinygo-org/tinygo/blob/v0.40.1/src/examples/hello-wasm-unknown/main.go)). Avoid **`//go:export`** / legacy command-style WASM patterns for new code; prefer **`//go:wasmexport`** (supported in TinyGo since 0.34) so exports stay **source-aligned** with `gc` Go’s wasmexport story ([Go blog](https://go.dev/blog/wasmexport)).
- Write code that stays **TinyGo-compatible**: avoid packages or constructs TinyGo does not support or only partially supports ([stdlib / language support](https://tinygo.org/docs/reference/lang-support/stdlib/)). Prefer **`core`**, **`assets`**, **`params`**, and **`compact/*`** over **`engine`** inside the compact subtree so the WASM build does not pull the full interactive engine graph.
- **No** goroutines, channels, or `select`. Single-threaded; each Python worker holds one module instance and plays games serially.
- **Avoid allocations** on hot paths where practical; avoid `fmt` and string formatting in exported WASM entrypoints.
- **Exports**: use `//go:wasmexport` with **WASM-friendly signatures** — fixed-size integers (`int32` / `uint32` as appropriate). Prefer **one `int32` return** per export (e.g. value or error code), **integer parameters only**, matching the host embedding contract.
- **Globals**: one documented **singleton game** and **singleton params** in the WASM library package is intentional.
- **`init`**: do not rely on `init` for background work or non-deterministic setup.
- **Package dependencies**: avoid depending on the `eventlog` package in anything other than tests under `compact/`, including indirectly via the `engine` package, to avoid pulling in TinyGo-incompatible dependencies like `encoding/json`.

## Python bridge (`rl_agent/`, WASM path only)

- For package management and `uv run`, follow [rl-agent-python.mdc](rl-agent-python.mdc) (scoped to `rl_agent/`).
- Game stepping for the **WASM training client** targets **wasmtime** (or the chosen WASM runtime), not httpx/OpenAPI, once the bridge is implemented.

## Parity tests vs reference `GameState`

`ProceduralGameState` / `GameState` are **legacy** of exploratory design and may have other quirks. Holdings and the takeover pool are **`assets.AssetMix`** on both reference and compact paths. Operate-phase randomness uses **in-state PCG** (`SetRNGSeed` on `GameState`), aligned with the compact engine.

- **Ground truth** for parity is the **training-observable surface**: what `rest_api` exposes (see `stateResponse` in `src/cmd/rest_api/main.go`) — status, reason, round, emissions, players (including holdings as `assets.AssetMix`), last-round snapshot, **`TakeoverPool` as `assets.AssetMix`**.
- The eventual WASM module should expose **the same logical fields** as scalars/bitfields.
- If parity fails and the cause looks like **RNG seeding or draw-count drift** between harnesses, ambiguous rules, or other reference-only behavior: **stop and ask the project owner** before weakening tests or adding hacks; the owner may change the Go reference implementation so parity stays honest.

## Takeover pool (canonical model)

- Model the pool as **one `AssetMix`** (five buckets), same as player holdings and the reference engine.
- `TakeoverRuleForcedTakeover`: pool must be empty before finishing build when the rules say so; same outcomes as today’s rules.
- `TakeoverRuleVirtualOwner`: pool counts feed grid/emissions; mode split in buckets still matters for those assets.
